title: An Experiment to Stop Online Abuse Falls Short in Germany
content: Despite having one of the world’s toughest laws against online hate speech and harassment, Germany has struggled to contain toxic content ahead of its Sept. 26 election.

title: In Push to Tax the Rich, White House Spotlights Billionaires’ Tax Rates

title: In a setback for Apple, the European Union seeks a common charger for all phones.

title: Business groups are divided as China seeks self-reliance.
content: European companies warned on Thursday that China’s push to replace imports was harmful, but American companies are more eager to cooperate with Beijing.

title: Uncertainty swirls around China Evergrande as a payment deadline passes.
content: Despite the uncertainty, shares in the big property developer, which is burdened with huge debt, jumped 18 percent Thursday.

title: California governor signs bill that could push Amazon to change labor practices.
content: “The hardworking warehouse employees who have helped sustain us during these unprecedented times should not have to risk injury or face punishment,” Gov. Gavin Newsom said.

title: Biden Huddles With Democrats as Divisions Threaten His Agenda
content: Democrats are nearing a make-or-break moment for President Biden’s agenda, with party divisions imperiling top-priority legislation and fiscal crises looming.

content: But his plans face a tough road as pressure grows for big pharmaceutical companies to share their vaccine technologies with poorer nations.

title: F.D.A. Authorizes Pfizer Booster Shots for Older and At-Risk Americans
content: Regulators said that people over 65 or at high risk of severe Covid-19 were eligible for an extra shot, setting up a staggered national booster campaign.

title: The U.S. Is Lifting Travel Restrictions for Visitors. What Do the New Rules Mean?
content: The Biden administration will allow vaccinated international travelers to enter the United States, including those from previously banned countries. Details remain to be worked out, but here is what we know so far.

title: Facebook’s Chief Technology Officer to Step Down in 2022
content: Mike Schroepfer, who leads the company’s artificial intelligence and other technical efforts, said he planned to transition into a role as a senior fellow.

title: Mortgage Lender Cut Corners in Echo of 2008 Crisis, Ex-Executive Says

title: Join Us for a Conversation on the Business of Longevity

title: A low-carbon economy is cheaper than the costs of climate change, a report says.
content: The European Central Bank put the region’s economy under a microscope to assess the impact of climate change action and inaction.

title: Here’s What’s Behind Europe’s Surging Energy Prices
content: Britain and the rest of Europe are watching natural gas prices and utility bills soar, and Russia is coming under pressure to provide more gas.

title: Volkswagen’s truck unit warns that the chip crisis will undercut sales.

title: Facebook’s Good News
content: The tech giant has changed its playbook this year to rebut criticism, using its algorithm to promote positive stories about itself.

title: China Says It Won’t Build New Coal Plants Abroad. What Does That Mean?
content: Beijing is the undisputed king of coal, but the announcement at the United Nations General Assembly this week was cautiously welcomed by climate experts.

title: They Never Could Work From Home. These Are Their Stories.

title: Pressure Grows on U.S. Companies to Share Covid Vaccine Technology

title: Moderna vs. Pfizer: Both Knockouts, but One Seems to Have the Edge
content: A series of studies found that the Moderna vaccine seemed to be more protective as the months passed than the Pfizer-BioNTech vaccine. Here’s why.

title: Barcelona Takes on Airbnb
content: A new rule, the only one of its kind in a major European city, forbids short-term private-room rentals, adding fuel to the debate over how to control booming prepandemic tourism.

title: Jerome Powell says the Fed is reviewing its trading rules.
content: The Federal Reserve is embroiled in an unusual drama: Some officials traded stocks and other financial products last year, prompting calls for an investigation.
